Here's the full setup:

**AppShell.xaml**

```xml
<Shell xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
       xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
       xmlns:views="clr-namespace:MyApp.Views"
       x:Class="MyApp.AppShell"
       FlyoutBehavior="Flyout">

    <!-- Dashboard — single page, one flyout entry -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Dashboard" Icon="dashboard.png">
        <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:DashboardPage}" />
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Products — one flyout entry, two top tabs -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Products" Icon="products.png">
        <Tab Title="Products">
            <ShellContent Title="Active"
                          ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ActiveProductsPage}" />
            <ShellContent Title="Archived"
                          ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:ArchivedProductsPage}" />
        </Tab>
    </FlyoutItem>

    <!-- Settings — single page, own flyout entry -->
    <FlyoutItem Title="Settings" Icon="settings.png">
        <ShellContent ContentTemplate="{DataTemplate views:SettingsPage}" />
    </FlyoutItem>
</Shell>
```

**AppShell.xaml.cs**

```csharp
namespace MyApp;

public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(Views.ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ContentTemplate` with `DataTemplate`** — pages load on demand, not at startup.
- **Two `ShellContent` inside one `Tab`** — this produces **top tabs** ("Active" / "Archived") under the Products flyout entry.
- **`productdetails` route** — registered for push navigation since it's not in the visual hierarchy.

**Navigate to details from a product list:**

```csharp
// With a query string
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

// Or pass the full object
var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

**Receive the parameter in `ProductDetailsPage` or its ViewModel:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
        else if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            LoadProduct(id.ToString());
    }
}
```

The flyout will show three entries — **Dashboard**, **Products**, **Settings** — and tapping Products reveals the Active/Archived top tabs.
